The agent's current objective is to answer the user's question about tracking mouse movements and changing the background color dynamically in a web page. Previously, the agent explained the `onerror()` event handler for handling errors during web page or resource loading. Now, the focus shifts to mouse events and background color manipulation.

To track mouse movements and change the background color, the `mousemove` event can be used. This event triggers whenever the mouse moves over an element. By attaching a function to this event, you can dynamically change the background color of an element based on the mouse's position or other conditions.

Here is an example of how to implement this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Mouse Tracking Example</title>
<style>
  body {
    height: 100vh;
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
  }
  div {
    width: 200px;
    height: 200px;
    background-color: blue;
  }
</style>
<script>
  document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
    const box = document.querySelector('div');
    box.addEventListener('mousemove', function(event) {
      // Change background color based on mouse position
      const x = event.clientX;
      const y = event.clientY;
      const red = Math.floor((x / window.innerWidth) * 255);
      const green = Math.floor((y / window.innerHeight) * 255);
      const blue = 255 - red;
      box.style.backgroundColor = `rgb(${red}, ${green}, ${blue})`;
    });
  });
</script>
</head>
<body>
<div></div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `mousemove` event is attached to a `div` element. As the mouse moves over the `div`, the background color changes based on the mouse's position relative to the window size. The `event.clientX` and `event.clientY` properties provide the coordinates of the mouse cursor within the viewport, which are then used to calculate RGB values for the background color.

By using mouse events like `mousemove`, developers can create interactive and dynamic web pages that respond to user input, enhancing the overall user experience.

